Project 5: Identify Fraud from Enron Email¶

Created by: Layne Newhouse¶

Submitted: January 10, 2017¶

Background Information¶

In 2000, Enron was one of the largest companies in the United States. By 2002, it had collapsed into bankruptcy due to widespread corporate fraud. In the resulting Federal investigation, a significant amount of typically confidential information entered into the public record, including tens of thousands of emails and detailed financial data for top executives. In this project, we will be playing detective by building a person of interest identifier based on financial and email data made public as a result of the Enron scandal. Labels will be provided via a hand-generated list of persons of interest in the fraud case, which means individuals who were indicted, reached a settlement or plea deal with the government, or testified in exchange for prosecution immunity. Features for the dataset include a subset of financial features as well as email features as follows:

Financial Features: ['salary', 'deferral_payments', 'total_payments', 'loan_advances', 'bonus', 'restricted_stock_deferred', 'deferred_income', 'total_stock_value', 'expenses', 'exercised_stock_options', 'other', 'long_term_incentive', 'restricted_stock', 'director_fees'] (all units are in US dollars)

Email Features: ['to_messages', 'email_address', 'from_poi_to_this_person', 'from_messages', 'from_this_person_to_poi', 'shared_receipt_with_poi'] (units are generally number of emails messages; notable exception is email_address, which is a text string)

POI Label: [poi] (boolean, represented as integer)

Project Tasks¶

  1. Select features
  2. Identify and remove outliers
  3. Create new features
  4. Analyze a variety of classifiers
  5. Tune a chosen classifier to achieve > 0.3 precision and recall
  6. Dump the classifier, dataset and feature list

#allocation across classes (POI/non-POI)
def total_classes(dataset):
    poi = 0
    people = 0
    for person in dataset:
        people += 1
        if dataset[person]["poi"]==1:
            poi += 1
    poi_pct = 100*float(poi)/people
    print "Number of POIs in the Dataset:",poi,"(%0.2f%%)"%poi_pct
    print "Number of Non-POIs in the Dataset:",people-poi,\
                                                "(%0.2f%%)"%(100-poi_pct)
    return poi

poi = total_classes(enron_data)

Number of POIs in the Dataset: 18 (12.33%)
Number of Non-POIs in the Dataset: 128 (87.67%)

By analyzing the data with the snippets of code above, we can start to understand what our dataset looks like and what each of the of the features have to offer in terms of the number and percentage of datapoints (or people) with missing values for each individual feature.

Before removing any 'bad data' or outliers from our data, we see that we have 146 data points (people) in the dataset. Of those people, 18 (12.3%) are labeled as Persons of Interest (POIs) and 128 (87.7%) are labeled as Non-POIs. With such a small dataset and a small pool of data points being classified as 'true' for being a POI we must be careful with the removal of outliers as well as the way in which we train and test our classifiers. Such precautions would be to not remove POIs unless absolutely needed as well as using the entire dataset to train our classifier and then validate it using a stratified shuffle as opposed to a simple test/train split. (We will go into further detail of this in the following sections).

#number of features used
def total_features(dataset):
    features = []
    for key, value in dataset.iteritems() :
        for item in value:
            if item not in features:
                features.append(item)
    print "Number of Features Available:", len(features)
    return features

As seen from above, there are 21 features available in the dataset, one of them being the POI label. By printing out the labels we can verify that they are indeed legitimate labels (in terms of the strings themselves). Next we tallied the number of 'NaN's in each label and compared them against the POI allocations. Here we observe that there are a number of features that have a significant amount of missing values for POIs. By creating a quick plot, we can see that there are a group of three features with over 90% of the POIs missing values for and one feature with over 70% of the POIs missing values for. Since we only have 18 POIs to begin with, features in which many POI's don't have values for will not provide a lot of information on how to identify the POIs and will likely confuse our classifiers since any NaN's will be later converted into zeros. Therefore, the following features will be removed from the analysis:

The problem, as stated above, with having too many NaNs they will eventually all converted into zeros and then processed by the classifiers. Thus if there was a large group of people that were all classified as Non POI and had many missing feature values the classifiers could wrongly associate these missing feature values, or zeros, as being a trait of Non-POIs.

The visualization above shows us the amount of people that have x features missing from the total feature set, x being denoted on the x-axis. Since we do not want to remove any POIs from the dataset, we will remove all datapoints that have 11 or more missing feature values.

#searching for the outlier
def find_largest_value(dataset, feature_name):
    outlier_name = ""
    largest_value = 0
    for key, value in enron_data.iteritems():
        inside_dict = value
        for k, v in inside_dict.iteritems():
            if (k == feature_name) & (v != 'NaN'):
                if v > largest_value:
                    largest_value = v
                    outlier_name = key
    print outlier_name, largest_value

When adding features, we can use our own human intuition and multiply or divide certain features together if we believe we can derive additional information from doing so. Later on in this project we will be using feature selection methods such as SelectKBest which will select the best remaining features and thus we do not have to be concerned at this point if the additional features we create are in fact better than the original ones.

There are two financial features in particular that I would like, the first being bonus over salary, i.e. how many times larger is an employees bonus than their salary. I think this could provide potential insight since an employee that did something illegal or fraudulent might be given a larger bonus as incentive to committing that act. But with this said, bonuses can range quite a bit depending on the person's position and/or seniority and thus the number of times larger a bonus is than the salary gives us a more relative number to go off of. The same thought pattern is true for my second financial feature that I will add which is total stock value over salary.

In [31]:
#calculates pearson correlation (r)
def corrfunc(x, y, **kws):
    r, _ = stats.pearsonr(x, y)
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.annotate("r = {:.2f}".format(r),
                xy=(.1, .9), xycoords=ax.transAxes)
    
def pair_grid(dataframe, filename):
    g = sns.PairGrid(dataframe)
    g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter)
    g.map_diag(sns.distplot, kde=False)
    g.map_lower(corrfunc)
    g.savefig(filename)

In the notebook it is difficult to see the grid above in detail so we save the plot as a .png file and view it separately. Upon opening this grid in a separate file it can be seen that the distributions across the horizontal are generally skewed (which verifies our need to transform the data), there are no more outliers that make the scatter plots unreadable, and there is a very high correlation between the variables total_stock_value and exercised_stock_options.

In [33]:
features = ["total_stock_value", "exercised_stock_options"]
pair_grid(financial_df[features], "pairgrid_stocks.png")

Pearson correlation or r-value is a measure of the linear dependence between two variables, i.e. how much of 'Y' is predicted by 'X'. Since the description of these variables are both regarding Enron stocks, and their correlation is close to one, we can see that having both of these variables does not add a great deal of additional information to our model. What it will do is add additional unnecessary weight to the underlying stock feature since the classifier will in effect be seeing an almost identical feature twice.

Instead of dropping one of the variables arbitrarily we can use principle component analysis (PCA) for dimensionality reduction i.e. combine the two features into one while minimizing information loss. When doing this we will get values that are both positive and negative as PCA works by creating a new origin that is centered in the data where the x-axis is directed along the 'principle axis of variation' (which would be similar to the line created by a linear regression). Since we are going to be doing a log10 transformation on our financial features we won't want any negative values and so I will shift the data such that the minimum value lies on the origin (0).

In [34]:
pca = PCA(n_components=1)
stocks = pca.fit_transform(financial_df[features])
stocks = stocks-min(stocks)
financial_df["pca_stocks"] = stocks
#plot new pca stock feature with former stock features
features = ["total_stock_value", "exercised_stock_options", "pca_stocks"]
pair_grid(financial_df[features], "pairgrid_stocks_pca.png")
#drop former stock features
features = ["total_stock_value", "exercised_stock_options"]
financial_df = financial_df.drop(features, 1)

From the pair grid plot above we can see that our new feature, pca_stocks, is a hybrid feature of total_stock_value and exercised_stock_options as can be seen by the respective correlation coefficients (r-values) of 0.99 and 0.98.

With that finished we can now go ahead and take the log10 transformation of the remaining financial features.

In [35]:
def add_one(array):
    new_array = [x+1 for x in array]
    return new_array
In [36]:
def log10(array):
    #adding 1 to the feature data to prevent log10(0)=undefined
    new_array = [x+1 for x in array]
    new_array = np.log10(new_array)
    return new_array

Picking and Tuning a Machine Learning Algorithm¶

When choosing an algorithm, you must first classify your dataset in terms of supervised / unsupervised and discrete / continuous. With regards to the Enron dataset we will be looking for a discrete, supervised learning algorithm. It is supervised because we already have labels for our data i.e. POI = True/False and discrete since all of the feature data is with regards to a separate employee. The following are a few machine learning algorithms that fall under this category:

  • Decision Tree
  • Naive Bayes
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM)
  • Ensembles
    • (Random Forest Classifier, AdaBoost Classifier)
  • K Nearest Neighbour

Some of the algorithms listed above require feature scaling such as SVM. Feature scaling rescales the values of each feature from 0 to 1 and without it, these algorithms computation speeds can be so slow that they become impractical to use. Algorithms that don't need feature scaling will be unaffected by the scaling and thus we can scale each feature before handing them off regardless of the classifier.

Currently we have 21 features which is likely a lot more than the classifiers will need. As we had done before with the correlated stock data, we can use PCA to reduce the number of features in our dataset while increasing the amount of information each of the remaining features possess. Unlike the stock data which had similar magnitudes, the 21 features that we will be inputting to PCA vary significantly in magnitude. Since PCA will be looking to align the new x-axis in the direction of largest variance we will also need to use feature scaling before principle component analysis.

Finally, we will use sklearn's SelectKBest function to select 'K', a chosen integer, best features that have the highest f-value for classification.

In [49]:
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('scale1', MinMaxScaler()),
        ('pca', PCA()),
        ('scale2', MinMaxScaler()),
        ('skb', SelectKBest())
    ])
param = {
        'pca__n_components':randint(9,19),
        'skb__k':randint(1,10)
    }

Using the pipeline feature I will be able to iterate through parameters a set number of times. Each time and random integer between 8 and 18 will be selected for the PCA components and an integer between 1 and 8 will be selected for SelectKBest K value. Since we are selecting K features from the PCA dimensionality reduction, K must be less than n_components. Although the cut-off number 8 is not an optimized number, it will prove as a good starting point for our analysis.

Edit: After looking at the parameters that made up the final estimator I saw that n_components and k both equated to 8. This gave me reason to slightly adjust these parameter values and observe the effect it would have on the final output metrics. After a few adjustments I found that a cut-off number of 9 was better suited for the given dataset and thus the changes were made to the 'param' section above.

Next we will use the sklearn documentation for each of the classifiers listed to outline parameters for each model. This step is extremely important due to the fact that each algorithm is going to work differently depending on the size, shape and contents of the dataset. On top of this, within each algorithm, with the exception of Gaussian Naive Bayes, there are a number of adjustable parameters that will have a significant impact on the output of the respective algorithm.

Let us take a look at the 'C' parameter in the SVM classifier. This happens to be a penalty parameter of the error term which is a function of the classifier. This term as default is set to C=1, but we don't know, for our particular dataset, if 1, 10, 50 or 150 is the most optimal value for C. Instead of creating the list [1, 10, 50, 150] and having the function GridSearch test each parameter in the list, I will set a minimum and maximum value, which is subject to fine tuning later, and having the function RandomSearch pick a random value between that minimum and maximum number. Two reasons that I will be using this method instead of GridSearch is first, I can adjust how many iterations I want to go through without having to arbitrarily pick and choose the numbers that I would like to keep. Second, the optimal number for any parameter is not likely going to be a 10, 50, 100 etc. and is more likely going to be some integer between those numbers like 42. Thus once I find the algorithm that I am comfortable spending more time with I can do a more thorough search on it's parameters.

Next we build a function that will take in the classifiers, parameter list, and dataset, searches 'n' number of times for the parameters that results in the highest F1 score, and then perform a longer, more thorough test, on the chosen parameters for each respective classifier.

Since our dataset has only 17 POIs we could potentially lose a significant amount of information by splitting our data into separate test train sets. One way to get around this is by using function called StratifiedShuffleSplit. This function splits the data n_splits times in different test/train sections and then averages across all of the results to find the optimal parameters allowing us to effectively train against the entire dataset.

In [52]:
def search_test_clf(n_iter, n_splits, clfs, dataset, feat_list, fp=False):
    
    best_score = 0
    data = featureFormat(dataset, feat_list, sort_keys = True)
    labels, features = targetFeatureSplit(data)
    cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=n_splits, random_state=42, 
                                          test_size=0.3)
    start = time()
    for i in range(0,len(clfs[0])):
        print clfs[0][i], "------------------------------------------"
        t0 = time() 
        warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
        rs = RandomizedSearchCV(clfs[1][i], param_distributions=clfs[2][i],
                                n_iter=n_iter, scoring='f1', cv=cv,
                                random_state=42)
        rs.fit(features, labels)
        search_time = round(time()-t0, 3)
        t0 = time() 
        test_classifier(rs.best_estimator_, dataset, feat_list, 1000, fp)
        print "Search/Fit Time:", search_time, "s", "   Test Time:",\
                                                round(time()-t0, 3), "s", "\n"
            
        if rs.best_score_ > best_score:
            best_rs = rs
            clf_name = clfs[0][i]
    
    print "\nTotal Run Time:", round(time()-start, 3), "s"
    print "Best Classifier:", clf_name
    return best_rs

n_iter represents the number of random searches that will be performed on each classifier being tested. n_splits is the number of test/train splits that will be created for each iteration of random classifier parameters. The parameters which achieve the highest average F1 score across the n_splits will then be tested against with the test_classifier function which then tests the winning parameters and classifier over 1000 splits of StratifiedShuffleSplit. We can test the final parameters over this many splits since we are only doing it once per classifier, but for searching purposes, having this many splits can be computationally expensive and thus a smaller number of splits (n_splits) will be used when searching for our parameters.

Before running our searching algorithm, I found it useful to test the Gaussian Naive Bayes classifier on the dataset without any feature selection or use of pipelines to make sure that as we add levels of complexity to our classifiers, we are in fact improving the results.

In [53]:
test_classifier(GaussianNB(), dataset, feature_list)

Accuracy: 0.63308   Precision: 0.28071   Recall: 0.76900   F1: 0.41128

Having now seen the results for the Gaussian Naive Bayes classifier, this is a good opportunity to talk about some of these evaluation metrics a discuss why we are using the F1 score as our RandomSearch evaluation metric. Definitions:

  • True Positive (TP) = Correctly Identifying a POI
  • True Negative (TN) = Correctly Identifying a Non-POI
  • False Positive (FP) = Predicting a Non-POI as a POI
  • False Negative (FN) = Predicting a POI as a Non-POI

To begin we look at accuracy, which is often a default metric for scoring algorithms. Accuracy describes the number of correctly predicted labels (POIs) out of all of the total number of predictions.

  • Accuracy = (TP+TN)/(TP+TN+FP+FN)

When dealing with a dataset which has a small number of true positives, such as the Enron dataset which has 17 POIs out of 128, accuracy can be misleading. This is because if an estimator is created which always predicts Non-POI, we would have predicted zero POIs and yet have an accuracy of 87% {(0+111)/(128)}.

  • Precision = TP/(TP+FP)
  • Recall = TP/(TP+FN)

Precession and Recall are two performance metrics that work well together when dealing with datasets like this one, as they focus in on the number of correctly identified 'true' labels. Precision gives us the number of correctly predicted positives out of the total number of positive predicted labels. Recall, on the other hand, gives us the number of correctly predicted positives out of the total number of positive labels, in other words, what percentage of the true labels were we able to recall.

The F1 score is a hybrid score of precision and recall which makes it a great evaluator for our classifier's parameters.

  • F1 = 2 x Precision x Recall / (Precision + Recall)

Conclusion¶

After trying multiple classifier parameter combinations and running a significant number of iterations on RandomSearchCV in attempt to bring up my precision and recall numbers, what ended creating the greatest increase in metrics scores was going back and adjusting and creating new features. The value in doing proper cleaning of the data, transformations, and adding new features really stood out to me when creating this project.

If the dataset had been a few magnitudes larger then it was, SVM would not have been a reliable classifer as it it took around 6 times longer to compute then some of the other classifiers such as K Neighbours. Also it was not until the last few adjustments in the features that SVM took the lead in terms of producing the highest F1 score. This goes to show that there is no one size fits all machine learning classifier and it really comes do to a dataset by dataset situation.

One of the ideas that I had to further improve this project was to have more of an adaptable parameter selection where instead of having a random integer for each parameter on each search we could implement a normal distribution centered around parameter values yielding the highest F1 scores. The same could apply to allocating more computational resources towards classifiers that are yielding higher results and lessen the searches on the classifiers that aren't doing as well.

Bonus (Exploring Abstract Features)¶

When creating the hybrid finance/email features I had made the mistake of dividing previously logged features. When you divide two logged values of the same base the following happens:

logb(x) = logc(x) / logc(b)

This is called the logarithm base change rule. Having done this, I had created features that such as log base(rec_poi/total_rec) of total_payments whose value reads; x where x is the number of times (the ratio of received emails from a poi divided by the total number of emails received) is multiplied by itself until it equals total_payments. This feature doesn't make any sense but it's ability to somehow group the POIs made it difficult for me to add it to this project.

def remove_classifier(target, clfs):
    for i in range(0,len(clfs[0])):
        if clfs[0][i] == target:
            clfs[0].remove(clfs[0][i])
            clfs[1].remove(clfs[1][i])
            clfs[2].remove(clfs[2][i])
            break

Summary¶

The goal of the project was to create a classifier that is able to identify persons of interest (POIs), using publicly available financial and email features, with evaluation metric scores, recall and precision, greater than 0.3. Machine learning algorithms are helpful tools for these types of classification problems and can customized to suite the needs of the particular dataset. A list of POIs has been provided for this dataset which means we should be using a supervised machine learning algorithm. Outliers in this dataset were detected visually and discretion was used to evaluate whether or not the outlier should remain in, or be removed from the dataset, based on validity and POI label status.

The features that were used in the dataset are as listed below. Some of these features were created from the original dataset and some of the original dataset features were removed as in described in the body of this project.

In [66]:
no_poi_fl = list(feature_list)
no_poi_fl.remove("poi")
print "No. Features:", len(no_poi_fl), "\n", no_poi_fl

No. Features: 26 
['salary', 'total_payments', 'bonus', 'deferred_income', 'expenses', 'other', 'long_term_incentive', 'restricted_stock', 'bonus/salary', 'stock/salary', 'pca_stocks', 'to_messages', 'from_poi_to_this_person', 'from_messages', 'from_this_person_to_poi', 'shared_receipt_with_poi', 'rec_poi/total_rec', 'sent_poi/total_sent', 'payments/rec_poi_ratio', 'payments/sent_poi_ratio', 'log-rec_poi_ratio(payments)', 'log-sent_poi_ratio(payments)', 'log-rec_poi_ratio(stock-salary)', 'log-sent_poi_ratio(stock-salary)', 'log-rec_poi_ratio(bonus-salary)', 'log-sent_poi_ratio(bonus-salary)']

In the feature selection pipeline, we take these features and scale each of the features from 0 to 1 such that the principle component analysis (PCA) does no discriminate based on feature magnitude. After the scaling, we put all 26 features into the PCA which results in, in the case of our final estimator, 9 principle components which are an amalgamation of the 26 that had been selected. Following this step, we will do another 0 to 1 scaling of the PCA values, since PCA outputs both positive and negative values, and then select a random number of the best outputs created by PCA to make up the features that will go into the machine learning algorithms. This final number that is selected is less about the particular components of the PCA but more so I am trying to see what number of features work best for which classifiers.

In the end, with our 'bonus features', we used the K Neighbors Classifier which ended up giving us the best scoring metrics and also happened to have one of the quickest run times. This classifier worked better than the others listed in the previous sections but it should be noted that a change in the number of features or the addition of any other features that were not thought of in this project could have a significant impact on the classifier is best suited for the dataset.

Each of the classifiers have a list of tuneable parameters that allow you to completely customize the algorithm for your dataset. The drawback of this customizability is that if the parameters are not properly tuned your algorithm will not perform to it's potential. The methodology I used for tuning the parameters of this dataset was that I would begin by guessing a range of parameter values for each classifier and then use RandomSearchCV to go through and assess different combinations of parameters. I would go back and change the parameter ranges if I found that the best performing parameters were close to, or equal to, the minimum or maximum value that I had set for the range. Additionally, if the classifiers run time was too long I would adjust some of the parameters such as the ensemble's n_estimator parameter.

Validation is the way in which you test your machine learning algorithm's performance. Ideally, with a large dataset, you could split the data into a training set and a testing set such that you train your algorithm first on a section of data and then test it on a separate section of data that the algorithm has not seen yet. A classic mistake might be using the same dataset to train your algorithm that you use to test your dataset, which introduces a significant amount of bias into your test results. For this dataset, since we had such a small number of POIs and a small dataset as a whole, we did not have the luxury of performing a single test/train split as the number of training POIs would be far too limited for the algorithm to get a true understanding of what it means to be a POI. In order to combat this, I used cross-validation method called StratifiedShuffleSplit. This function does 1000 different test/train splits and then averages the results across all of the trials. This allows us to get a good understanding for the classifier-parameter combination while not having to worry about which datapoints made it into the training set and which did not.

As stated earlier: "Precession and Recall are two performance metrics that work well together when dealing with datasets like this one, as they focus in on the number of correctly identified 'true' labels. Precision gives us the number of correctly predicted positives out of the total number of positive predicted labels. Recall, on the other hand, gives us the number of correctly predicted positives out of the total number of positive labels, in other words, what percentage of the true labels were we able to recall. The F1 score is a hybrid score of precision and recall which makes it a great evaluator for our classifier's parameters."

The final estimator in this project was able to achieve the following scores: Precision: 0.57580, Recall: 0.40450 and F1: 0.47518. These values surpass the required precision and recall values of 0.3 by 92% and 35% respectively.
